reviewText: Why is it that movies such as this never find their place in the theaters, but "Million Dollar Baby" and the like are viewed by hundreds of thousands of people soon to be disappointed? That's what the world has come to, I guess.If you're not a fan of the cinemagic of "Crash", I don't necessarily suggest this movie for you, though it is a bit more intense. With the "cut and paste" cinematics that tell you numerous stories (in this case, 6 different storylines), this movie does not follow chronology. Instead, it offers you each persons story, and you begin to piece together how they all come together at 11:14 (that didn't ruin anything, I promise).This movie is truly beautiful, though you may want to be careful of the audience you are seeing it with. It's pretty intense.

reviewText: "11:14" is writer/director Greg Marcks' first feature film, and it is a unique and riveting look at the randomness of life, and how our lives interconnect amid the chaos of it. Starting with the imaginative titles, it's keeps one's interest for all of its 85 minute length. All the action takes place on a single night in "Middletown", which represents any small USA town, the kind that closes up by 9 PM. Only 10 characters (as well as an overworked policeman and 2 paramedics) are left to create a plot so clever one can see this film several times, and be entertained by it.The ensemble cast is fantastic, with Patrick Swayze (wearing a "fat suit" to hide his athletic physique) as Frank, the father of devious wench Cheri (Rachael Leigh Cook) and husband of Norma (Barbara Hershey). There is marvelous interaction between Buzzy and Duffy, 2 convenience store clerks, superbly played by Hilary Swank and Shawn Hatosy. Others in the fine cast include Henry Thomas as Jack, Clark Gregg as the beleaguered cop, and Stark Sands, Colin Hanks, and Ben Foster, as 3 kids out for a night of fun and mayhem.Filmed on a shoestring in 26 nights in Altadena, California, Marcks was only 24 when he wrote the script, and filmed it a year later. He is very articulate, and the excellent DVD extras include informative commentary by him, as well as a "making of" featurette, deleted scenes (the final one is terrific), and more. The music by Clint Mansell is also great and adds much to the film. Marcks says about the randomness of life that "perhaps there is a larger design...but we're incapable of seeing it", and the film is also about choices, whether or not one takes responsibility for those choices, and how they affect other people. Though some may find this film too bizarre, it is is a brilliant debut for Marcks, and I eagerly look forward to seeing his future work.

reviewText: At 11:14 PM in the tiny town of Middleton, several seemingly unrelated events will conspire together in order to bring judgement upon the unrighteous (or something like that). Hillary Swank, Patrick Swayze, Barbara Hershey, Henry Thomas, and Colin Hanks are among the many characters who become mere cogs in this hilariously bleak mobius-strip of doom! It all starts w/ an automobile accident that is not what it appears to be. From there, we are taken on a tour of Middleton via several different perspectives, each giving a small piece of the larger puzzle. The story involves deception, conspiracy, death, and extreme abuse of a corpse! Don't worry, it's all in good fun; and no matter how confusing it may seem, it all makes sense in the end. Rachael Leigh Cook is especially devilish in her role as Cheri, the gal w/ the movie's blackest soul. She is pure eeevil, and sets the whole thing in motion. Everyone else is sucked into her vortex of fate! 11:14 is highly recommended to anyone seeking something off-center. It is the exact opposite of CRASH, in that nothing is serious and no one walks away unscathed or "better" in some way. How refreshing...

reviewText: **CONTAINS SPOILERS**In the vein of LOVE ACTUALLY, 11:14 gives us a set of intersecting storylines but in a very black comedy way. And while I enjoyed LOVE ACTUALLY very much, 11:14 I enjoyed only marginally. Don't get me wrong, it is entertaining. But a few times during the viewing I said, "No way would it happen like that."11:14 focuses on several lives that are forever changed at exactly the same moment, and how each overlaps the other in strange and often chuckling ways. The film starts out with Jack (Henry Thomas, E.T.) driving down the road, half-drunk, when he runs over someone in his car. Terrified that he'll go to jail, he quickly tucks the body into the back of his car's trunk. Norma (Barbara Hershey) approaches the accident in her own car, sees Jack, and quickly surmises that he's hit a deer ("Happens all the time right around here"). She helpfully calls the police to notify them of the accident and drives away. Officer Hannagan (Clark Gregg) shows up on the scene and uncovers the truth. Or is it the truth? Did Jack really hit and kill this guy?We back-pedal to another group of lives, a trio of young boys out for a good time. They're driving around, drinking, and letting ...um ...everything hang-out. In fact, one of them decides to pee out the window and it is during this time that the driver accidentally runs into a young woman in the middle of the road, instantly killing her. How terrible. Or is it? In the process of slamming on the brakes, the young man who was peeing out the window loses his manhood, too. Ouch!Another set involves Buzzy (Hilary Swank) and Duffy (Shawn Hatosy) who are workmates at a local convenience store. Duffy needs cash and decides to rob the store (with Buzzy's approval). Trouble is, Buzzy wants him to wound her so that it looks like she was trying to protect the store and won't get fired. A gunshot overheard. A bowling ball. A missing set of keys. All of these things lead to some rather outlandish yet darkly funny hijinks.The final set of lives (mostly) are the family of the aforementioned Norma (Hershey). She's married to Frank (Patrick Swayze) and they have a daughter named Cheri (Rachael Leigh Cook) whom starts all of this pandemonium. It is her who is on the phone with Jack (Thomas) at the beginning of the film and it is this that causes Jack to get into the "accident". It is also Cheri who is responsible for the death of a young man by having sex with him in a cemetery and causing a headstone to fall on his head, thus crushing his brains out. She's not a very nice lady, out for "the money", and she's using everyone, including her father, in order to get what she wants. She is the one who's responsible for the dead guy that Jack hits; he didn't run-over and kill anyone. It was Cheri's father throwing the body of the bashed-in-brains guy off an overpass and landing on Jack's car. She's also the young woman who gets hit and killed by the trio of boys out having a good time. And she's been pretending to be pregnant and needing money from her boyfriends in order to get an abortion. One of these boyfriends, as it turns out, is Duffy, who would use the money from his robbery in order to pay for Cheri's procedure. But her death puts a quick end to that and closes pandora's box.Twisting the viewer's perceptions is the game here, and it's pulled off pretty well. The story was entertaining and I kept watching, only to be amazed at how these lives intersected.The only downside is the impossibility of certain aspects. Most notably is the cop, Officer Hannagan, who is the only law enforcement official we ever see. Considering all of the death, shooting, accidents, and other bizarre occurrences, the police would've been swarming over these scenes. But no. All we see is one lone officer with no crime scenes. Not likely.Still, the story moves along a great clip and the audience is entertained by the unfolding stories.
summary: Love Actually Meets The Dark Side

reviewText: It's really a lot of fun reading the reviews of this movie. Some folks become deeply philosophical, and say it represents the randomness of life. Others compare it with "Crash" which is a bit ludicrous. "Crash" is a serious movie about race relations. "11:14" is, pay attention now, a COMEDY. Yes, a very black comedy, involving a couple of hilarious accidental deaths. If you can't conceive of accidental deaths as terribly funny, then this movie is not for you. And if you are a really macho male then a cast member's loss of a certain reproductive organ might also turn you off.If you want to compare this flick to another movie try "Freeway" with Reese Witherspoon. That's a really black humor classic that also went over the heads of a lot of people.This is a laugh a minute show for black humor lovers. One scene, where a body toppled off a bridge was so funny I had to put the DVD on pause until I could stop laughing.
summary: Hey Folks, Get With It. This Is a Comedy

reviewText: With the frenetic energy and pitch black humor of such movies as "Go" and "Pulp Fiction," "11:14" is a slick and stylish piece of first time filmmaking from writer/director Greg Marcks.  The film consists of several very clever overlapping stories that take place shortly after 11:00 PM in a sleepy middle American town where the sidewalks roll up after sunset.  Each episode rewinds briefly, outlining the particular events leading up to the pivotal 11:14 (PM).Jack (Henry Thomas) is driving home under the influence, distractedly chatting away with his girlfriend on his cell phone, when he suddenly hits something, shattering the windshield of his car.  Stunned, he screeches to a stop, coming to rest under a 'deer crossing' sign.  Getting out of the car, Jack encounters a passing motorist (Barbara Hershey) who cheerfully offers to call the police for him before she drives off.  Throwing away his open bottle of liquor, he discovers the body pinned under his car is not a deer after all.  Panic-stricken and alcohol impaired, Jack attempts to dispose of the body by stuffing it into the trunk of his car--just as the police drive up.  Elsewhere, a small group of teenagers (Colin Hanks, Ben Foster and Stark Sands) decide to embark on an evening of enthusiastic drive-by vandalism--culminating in disaster.  In another part of town, a precocious teenager, Cheri (Rachael Leigh Cook), runs out of the house to meet her boyfriend against the wishes of her disapproving father, Frank (Patrick Swayze).  A few minutes later, while walking his dog through the church cemetery located next door to his house, Frank discovers his daughter's car keys lying next to a mutilated corpse.  Jumping to the conclusion that his daughter must have fought off and killed her 'would be' date-rapist, Frank decides to get rid of the body and any evidence connecting her to the crime.  Meanwhile, a convenience store clerk, Buzzy (Hilary Swank), is getting ready to close up when her friend, Duffy (Shawn Hatosy), shows up with a poorly thought out plan to come up with the money to pay for his girlfriend's abortion.  The last story returns to the home of Frank and Cheri, where Cheri prepares to bolt out the door to meet her date, and is the episode where the various storylines converge for the film's denouement.The movie is full of pranks that go horribly wrong, terrible judgment calls, and illogical conclusions that are leapt to--resulting in decisions that carry catastrophic consequences.  The serpentine plotlines are neatly tied together and kept lively by a terrific cast.  "11:14" is a wild darkhouse ride of a film.

reviewText: I must say that, unlike a lot of people who have viewed this film, I found it to be hysterically funny!  It must be noted, however, that the movie has a macabre sense of humor.  This isn't a "feel good" sort of comedy, so if that's what you're looking for, this one isn't for you.The story takes place in a small town and shows how the lives of various townspeople have their lives intertwined.  In particular, the core of the movie focuses on a theme that all virtually all of us worry about:  striking a pedestrian with our vehicle.  In the midst of hit & runs, the characters do a lot of really stupid things, which in-turn leads to the comedic aspect of the film.Some people have compared the present DVD toCrash (Widescreen Edition).  The films have similarities in two ways:  they both detail chance-encounters and both stories are scrambled like an omelet rather than being told in a straightforward linear fashion.  Beyond that, I would hesitate to stretch the comparsions too far.Crash (Widescreen Edition)is a somber drama with poignant insights into the human condition.  Meanwhile, 11:14 simply doesn't take itself too seriously.If you're looking for a "different" sort of movie that's not a rehash of an old cinematic formula, which one is worth a whirl. Patrick Swayze, Barbara Hershey and Hilary Swank are great, and the movie features a wuvable Golden Retriever who steals the show!

reviewText: One of the great physical laws is cause and effect. However, the vocabulary is limited, especially in the use of a certain four letter F word.Really, do current teenagers have such limited vocabularies?  If so, then the SAT is a waste of time and money.Back to the film, it was good to see Patrick Swayze playing such a different type of character-an overly concerned father with his own issues.  Clark Gregg gave an outstanding performance as the police officer who had to deal with all of these events leading up to 11:14.If this is your genre, then it is worth your ninety minutes.  If not, don't waste your time or money on this film.

reviewText: Greg Marcks offers us in '11:14' that rare breed of film that keeps us on the edge of our seats for the entire 95 minutes running time.  This strangely wonderful tale embraces the ideas of consequences and serendipity by unraveling a story of two deaths that affect the lives of eight kids and two parents, each with separate perceptions of shared incidents, and all of those perceptions intertwine in the most unique way imaginable.  This is not a teen horror flick, not an attempt to do an imitation cheap movie like 'Blair Witch Project' look-alikes.  '11:14' is simply a fine script played with comedy and tragedy and wide-eyed wonderment by a top notch cast of actors.To relate the tale would to defray the anxiety Marcks creates in his writing.  It is sufficient to say that little nerdy people in a small town somewhere are all caught up in two deaths, a thwarted robbery, a case of missing bodies, and a final core explanation of how the whole foolish mess got started. Along the way there are hilarious moments of accidental death during intercourse in a grave yard, a severed penis and its impact on hit and run kids, a rather randy and hormone driven trashy girl whose parents get caught up in the scheme of things... and that is only starters.The exceptional cast includes Hilary Swank (with braces), Patrick Swayze (with body padding), Barbara Hershey obsessed with opera, Rachel Leigh Cook as the promiscuous round robin girl, Henry Thomas as a drunk driver, Ben Foster as the genital loser, Blake Heron, Shawn Hatosy, Blake Heron, Stark Sands, Colin Hanks, and Gregg Clark as the revolving police officer who tries to keep up and make sense of the mess.The cinematography is beautifully handled by Shane Hurlbut who manages to keep the nighttime ambience all centered on the 11:14 PM restrictions of the action. But above all it is the brilliant script and tight direction by Marcks that makes this the strong, grossly overlooked sleeper of a movie that it is.  It just has everything!  Grady Harp, October 05

reviewText: Forget the popcorn. Make yourself a nice sandwich. By the time Patrick Swayze munches through his lines you'll want it. What you have here is a fine ensemble cast performing for a new writer-director that Hollywood seems to have overlooked because they were too busy financing blockbusters that bombed at the box-office.What makes this film work is its exacting attention to detail. No loose ends. You'll encounter a full spectrum of emotions and the ending might not be to your liking but you'll have fun.No shaky closeups, filtered color, or wild camera angles. Just plain good filmaking. Don't forget the commentary, it's worth it. Enjoy your sandwich.

reviewText: I wish that 'Crash' would've had the same integrity or freshness of screenwriting and direction as this film, not to mention 'Crash's profuse amount of soapbox preaching about society, or its caricatures of people, both of which 11:14 are selflessly devoid.That said, stepping off my own disgruntled soapbox and with apologies in advance, as I'd normally otherwise hate to compare films, or the results and awards of films, or maybe I got your attention, let's look into 11:14:We're presented with a strange and inconclusive situation on an apparently everyday night on some unknown stretch of highway.  A drunk man makes a call from his vehicle on his cell phone.  An accident occurs and he is left bewildered, completely unsure of what has happened.  This is only the first couple of minutes, so I haven't revealed anything, yet the plot revolves around this strange coincidence.What happens beyond that I won't say, for your sake, to preserve both the film's integrity, as well as that of the audience, but everything is told in pieces.  If you're a fan of Kurosawa's Rashomon, which was made over 50 years before this in a slightly similar style, you'll appreciate the retelling of the story from different perspectives, although you might not necessarily enjoy the ending in the same way.Although the story seems to come full circle and quite complete from all perspective, you might be left at the end with many questions, which may be a point of the film.I'd encourage everyone to see this at least once.  The direction, acting all around (including none less than Hillary Swank as an amazingly and delightfully awkward, charming and hilarious, but believable character, not to mention Henry Thomas, Rachel Leigh Cook, and the supporting cast), editing, screenwriting and cinematography are worth no less than one view.  No less, and many more, in my opinion.  I just saw this, and I decided to get the DVD (used) to see it again.
summary: The movie that I wished "Crash" would've been

reviewText: I watched this rather bizarre movie not knowing what to expect.  Part way through I was hooked, and by the end I thought, "wow, what a clever movie."  The movie seems somewhat improbable, dead bodies falling onto cars, an employee robbing his place of employment, a guy losing his genitals, but the end result was a well directed, well acted film.What makes this movie a challenge to watch is how it works backwards from the climactic scene.  The movie thus becomes a series of vignettes that evolve around the preceeding (succeeding) event.  The viewer knows when each scene ends as the camera focuses on a clock.  The end result is an event that happens at 11:14 though that is really the opening scene in the film.With less capable actors, this film may have crashed and burned, but this cast is able to work with the director to make an entertaining, if off-beat, film.

reviewText: The time is, 11:14. A young man is headed down a highway.Suddenly, a body falls onto the young man's car.This is how the new dynamic, original film by, Greg Marcks begins. reviewText: In the vein of such films as Crash, 21 Grams, and Memento; 11:14 presents a slightly different, more complicated story. We're given a series of vignettes of coincidences occuring in the lives of several people, that may not be coincidence at all. I don't remember this movie even being in theatres, butthe performances, complex script, and fast moving story make this movie one of the best films of 2005. In the beginning we see a man named Jack (Henry Thomas) who's a bit drunk, driving down the road when he apparently hits someone. The second vignette feautres three kids (Colin Hanks, Ben Foster, and Stark Sands) driving down the road, when they hit a young woman and one of the kids loses his wang. The third story, we see a man named Frank (Patrick Swayze) trying to cover up a murder, that might've been commited by his daughter. In the fourth story, we meet Duffy(Shawn Hatosy) deparately trying to get up the $500 dollars for his girlfriend's abortion. To do this, Duffy must convince Buzzy (Two-time Oscar winner Hilary Swank) to let him rob the store that both he and she work at. The fifth story pretty much puts the movie into focus, so I'll avoid a synopsis for that one. Now, this movie is extremely close to perfect. The only real problem is that all of these characters are stupid, don't know who to trust, and make decisions that could have been solved in a much easier way.Despite a cast of mostly unknowns (except for Swank, Swayze, Barbara Hershey, Rachel Leigh Cook, and possibly Colin Hanks & Ben Foster)this movie manages to work very well. Every single event, no matter how small it is, manages to click in with everything that happens. That's where writer/director Greg Marcks succeeds. The sad thing about this movie is that it doesn't get half the attention the three films I mentioned above, have gotten.This movie is only 80 minutes long, but every second is entertaining. You can barely tear yourself away from the screen. One more thing is that Marcks keeps you guessing. When you think you've figured out the entire story, there's one more twist waiting around the corner. So, as I said one of the best films of 2005 and certainly the most entertaining; Don't pass up11:14.GRADE: A+
summary: One of the Most Entertaining Films of 2005

reviewText: I guess Hilary Swank made this movie before she went into boxing in Clint Eastwood's MILLION DOLLAR BABY, but her portrayal here of the dentally challenged 7-11 clerk at the all night concenience store is definitely a sketch for her Oscar winning portrayal.  She must have hung out with some lower class people in order to ape them so brilliantly here and in the Eastwood film.  Marcks' commentary here says that her part was originally written for a boy, but when she moved in on the film and took a producer's credit, Swank had him re-write the part so she could play it.  I think if a man had played it as Greg Marcks had planned, it would have been more of a shock when you found out that "he" resented Shawn Hatosy's affair with Rachael Leigh Cook because "he" and Shawn had had something going on last summer.  Now it's just a jibe.  That's not to take away from Swank's fine acting, though someone might have asked her to tone down the braces just aa little bit.  She's worried about losing her job (which must pay her what, $6 an hour?) because she's the sole support of herself AND her sister who has TB?  And yet she has $12,000 worth of orthodontia filling her face, where'd she get the money for all that hardware.  Marcks' commentary is excellent at suggesting the pros and cons of working with a high-powered Oscar winner like Hilary Swank, who at that date was always trailed everywhere by her mournful hound-dog husband, the ineffectual yet sweet Chad Lowe.  It can't have been easy filming all these actors in a limited time frame and almost no budget.  They must have had Barbara Hershey, for example, from what, 10:30 at night till 11:45?And yet she gets to shine in her role as she has in few other studio pictures of recent years, as the mother of a tramp who seems strangely connected to the wild forest in which she and Patrick Swayze have built their eco-friendly home.  The movie suffers a bit towards the end, once you figure that neither Hershey nor Swank is likely to be further featured, but by that time other actors emerge from the murk to pick up the slack, and even some whom you might have written off, like Shawn Hatosy (from THE FACULTY) and Rachael Leigh Cook (from SHE'S ALL THAT) reveal they're not just pretty faces, they've got personality too, and talent galore.
summary: Tries to Do Something Different--and Succeeds

reviewText: A pretty remarkable movie. I agree with several reviewers that it's a shame that Hollywood, for all the good it does, decides for us what to push and what to shelve. Those of us who are avid readers, for example, are well aware that there is an entire legion of great first and second time authors who get few at-bats because publishers make similar decisions. See for example Eisler, Riordan, Crow, Landay, Ford, Gruber to name but a few. Haven't heard of them? Pity.And in the genre of the movies, how about this year's Oscar winner "Crash?" Made years ago on a tight budget and shelved because it lacked the panache of 'names.' So what happens this year? "Brokeback Mountain" with a voluptuous budget, great stars, great music, national debt-size marketing, loses to a movie with 1/10th the budget and no names. And I have to tell you I think Matt Dillon and Terence Howard out acted anybody eventually clutching the statue. But in the words of Dr. Watson, 'I digress.'11:14 is the first directorial entre' of Greg Marcks and he hits a homerun. Another movie like "The Red Eye" which I reviewed a few weeks back, that with some "push" from the sponsors, would have garnered a better following.It is similar to one of the greatest plots, the 'inadvertent' or 'accidental' presence at the moment of tragedy. Here, a series of unrelated vingettes bring diverse good and not so good people to an area where their inattention, foolishness and emotional fraud overlap. This type of movie remind me so much of Thornton Wilder's classic (and used to be required reading in the 10th grade . . . I wonder what happened?) about the 5 individuals on 'The Bridge at San Luis Rey' when it snaps and the 5 plummet to their deaths in the Peruvian gorge below. Leaving us and Brother Juniper with the question, what brought them there at the same time?"The Bridge" is a duality, battling between accidental connections and God's plan. Brother Juniper's search for God's meaning has him branded in heretical fashion. It may be that what we leave is not an imprint or even a memory but rather that we lived our lives aware of the power of love. Many who have spent a lifetime in passion can tell us less of love than the child that lost a dog yesterday, the book reminds us.And in 11:14, the time of the impact of all of these lives does that to the extent that it is random. Hilary Swank signed on for this 2003 movie, held until 2005, and now floated cautiously in video no doubt to some extent because of her rising star. Comical, graphic, occasionally idiotic, Swank and Colin Hanks do Mr. Marcks proud as lives begin and end at 11:14. I hope we see Mr. Marcks again as he has a real future. 4 stars. Larry Scantlebury
summary: What brought them to the bridge?

reviewText: This little film festival-art house movie, only 75 minutes in duration, is a mystery in the "Memento" and "Pulp Fiction" tradition. It tells a story about a sequence of events occurring at 11:14 p.m. in a small town involving a group of people and how all those people and events are interrelated.The film begins, with a great deal of interest, with an auto accident involving a drinking driver and a cell phone call. As this sequence unfolded -- especially after the police arrived -- I was reminded of a couple early Coen brothers moveis, especially "Blood Simple".As it went on, you see how all the principal actors are somehow related to this one event, which turns out to be a fatality for a couple people in a little town and the ruination of about a half-dozen other lives through chicanery, lying, deception, bad character and bad attitude. The single theme running through these events is bad timing linked to a very dark sense of humor.There are a lot of stars in this little movie -- Barbary Hersehy, Hilary Swank, Patrick Swayze -- and some others you are probably less familiar with. The actors all do OK jobs but the longer the movie goes on, the more contrived and disinteresting becomes the plot and, ergo, the less credible becomes the acting and characterization.So chalk this up as an interesting and partially successful initial feature for its producer that begins well, holds interest for awhile, but eventually overplays its hand and loses steam before its denouement. It's a good film that, at a mere 75 minutes, is probably more well-suited to play on Satruday night on a cable channel than in your home.Give it a try if you like any of the films I compared it with, but don't expect anything as good.
summary: Oddball feature starts out great, loses steam later

reviewText: I see a lot of comments on how writer-director Greg Marcks's film "11:14" is in the tradition of "Pulp Fiction," but that is true only to the extent that you are talking about a film that plays with chronology.  True, Quentin Tarantino made it possible to tell a story in a non-linear mode, but that is not what Marck does in this one.  What he does is more akin to Akira Kurosawa's "Rashomon," where we get the same story from various perspectives.  Even here the analogy is not completely on point either, because in "Rashomon" each character tells a decidedly different version, only the last of which is privileged as what really happened.  In "11:14" each pass through the story covers essentially the same time (each story starts progressively earlier in the evening), but for the most part in a different place.  The "most" part of that last sentence is key, because the characters and stories interconnect and as we learn something new we rethink what has gone out before.We begin with Jack Levine (Henry Thomas), who is driving along one night in the town of Middleton, talking on a cell phone, a bottle of booze on the front seat, when he gets disconnected from his call, the clock in his car hits 11:14 and a body hits his windshield.  The situation, to put it mildly, is not good, and they manage to get progressively worse for Jack (could YOU recite the alphabet backwards under pressure?).  I do not want to get into the details, because that would spoil the fun.  Suffice it to say this is only the first piece in this black comedy.  It is important you know that this is a black comedy because cars hitting people, or people hitting cars, are not usually topics of humor.  Besides, there are arguably worse things that happen to people in this movie (depending on your point of view, which very well may be gender specific).The rest of the cast, in alphabetical order, are Rachel Leigh Cook as Cheri, Ben Foster as Eddie, Colin Hanks as Mark, Clark Gregg as Officer Hannagan (who is having a very full night), Shawn Hatosy as Duffy, Blake Heron as Aaron, Barbara Hershey as Norma, Stark Sands as Tim, Hilary Swank as Buzzy, and Patrick Swayze as Frank.  I have no doubt that all of them were persuaded to go with Marck, whose only previous credit was the 19-minute long "Lector" (about a man who makes his living reading books to cigar rollers at a time when the new technology of the radio is threatening his job, on the basis of this script.  That is because this script adds a new layer of meaning to the story each time around as we come full circle and finally understand what really happened.  I agree with the fine ensemble cast that signed on for this one, that Marck pulls it off, and that what we end up with is not so much a cosmic joke as what might actually be cosmic justice.  The only question now is what does Marck do for an encore?  Because you can only play this type of game once.  The key thing is that when you do something like this, you do it as well as this solid little film.
summary: Just wait for all of the pieces to fit to figure out the puzzle in this black comedy

reviewText: It is a very busy evening for officer Hannagan, the lonely cop patrolling Middelton, a little town somewhere in USA. He will have his hands full with the robbery of a local grocery, a hit and run, a hit and no run, two dead bodies, one gunshot wound, 1200$ in cash, one bowling ball and a weird accident involving a severed... ahem, well let's just say that what was severed is usually not associated with female anatomy... After barely one hour of his service he will run out off handcuffs...It is clear that this movie was inspired a little by Quentin Tarantino, especially in its dialogues. The story is told backwards, in five chapters, every one being more hilarious than the previous... and they all interconnect with a total perfection! All the actors give a great performance, but Hillary Swank and Patrick Swayze are especially good (it is also a great pleasure to see Swayze again). For all those who loved "Dirty dancing" as much as I did, there is one scene with Swayze which you will simply love (no hints - watch the movie!).Two important lessons can be learned from this film:- if you need to go, you should REALLY stop the car...- getting intimate in a cemetary is a REALLY bad idea...Now, "11.14" of course is not an immortal masterpiece which will survive humanity itself - but if you want to pass a nice evening with a smart, dark, and slightly misantropic comedy, this is what you need.
summary: A really funny, quite smart, dark comedy

reviewText: Writer/director Greg Marckus certainly serves up a tasty little thriller in this underappreciated gem.  The movie focuses on the events leading up to a bizarre road accident, and intertwines them beautifully, keeping the audience wondering just what the heck is going on.  The cast is superb, with every character getting their own moments of glory, and the ending is truly surprising, but the kind that makes you smile and say, wow, this guy did a great script.  While the entire cast is flawless, standouts include Shawn Hatosy and Oscar winner Hilary Swank as hapless bank robbers; Rachael Leigh Cook's smarmy bad girl who is the true impetus of all the goings on; Patrick Swayze and Barbara Hershey as her parents; and Henry Thomas as our opening protagonist who plays a bigger part than we initially realize.  With a missing bowling ball and a severed male organ figuring into the plot, 11:14 is a refreshing and original movie that deserves more acknowlegement.

reviewText: 11:14 is a kind of cinematic puzzle, starting with a car crash and then working backwards until all the pieces of the puzzle are in place. The film is mostly about kids or young adults misbehaving and the intersecting, tragic consequences. But a grizzled Patrick Swayze gives a good performance as the frustrated and powerless father of the prime mischief-maker. The production values are good, the scene switches keep your attention and, while there really aren't any characters you identify (hopefully) too much with, you do want to keep watching until the puzzle is finally glued together and put on the wall. Oh, did I forget to mention that Hilary Swank, who went on to win an Oscar, has a juicy role in 11:14? Not exactly a date flick or a family film but nevertheless an enjoyable intellectual thriller when you are in a darker mood.

reviewText: ...Okay, maybe two thing. The movie was actually pretty good, and I don't have any major complaints, but there are two things that would have made this a spectacular movie and given it 5 stars instead of four.First, the movie starts off a bit slow. I found myself right at the beginning thinking I wasn't going to like it much, but about 1/2 way through, it really picked up and I was on the edge of my seat through the rest of it, trying to put all the pieces together before they were revealed.The second thing that would have made the movie better was if a bit more had been put into the production. The movie has a bit of a cheesy B grade horror film, and not a try suspense type feel to it that the movie actually is.The plot isn't really one plot, but rather a series of sub plot, small little stories that all lead up to one major event, or a series of events, that are all interrelated, and culminate in this one thing that happens at 11:14pm one evening.It's kind of a 'chaos theory' type story, in that one event leads to another, which leads to another, and then another, and so on and so forth, showing how several different seemingly unrelated events actually were related in some way. Seeing all the stories come together in the end, and realizing that the part of the movie at the beginning that I thought made it slow, really worked, I found I was both surprised to an extent and riveted.Definitely not disappointed in the movie at all, just wish that it had a major budget and was filmed a bit better. Other than that, I highly recommend the movie to anyone who likes suspense.
summary: Only one thing could have made it better...

reviewText: Director/writer Greg Marcks' black comedy opened in a few film festivals in 2003 and in Europe then finally went to DVD in 2005.  The movie deserves a better fate.  The unusually inventive story involves a cast of characters who evidently never made it past middle school given their overall stupidity.  Set in a small town, most have a nodding relationship with each other or are at least connected in some way.  Late one evening around 11, their paths criss-cross with horrific results.  The movie is remarkably coherent in spite of the logistical challenges.  An "A" list ensemble pulls it all together nicely.  Hilary Swank has a mouth full of braces playing a reluctant robbery victim in a convenience store.  Ben Foster, Colin Hanks and Stark Sands are van cruisin' high school mischief makers.  Patrick Swayze and Barbara Hershey the blue collar parents of Rachael Leigh Cook's slutty and pregnant high schooler.  Henry Thomas is a drunk driver on his way to pick up Cheri (Cook).  Jason Segel is a very skinny paramedic. And Clark Gregg is a police officer who is called to investigate the various crimes that all culminate at 11:14 PM.  This is a small movie worth checking out.

reviewText: Its a shame that I never even heard of this movie except by chance on amazon.com's list of "best movies you've never even heard of" (or something like that). As I read the list of actors in the film, I was surprised how this one fell through the cracks. It has Henry Thomas, Patrick Swayze, Barbara Hershey, Hilary Swank, Colin Hanks, Rachel Leigh Cook, and the always good Sean Hatosy. With a cast like that, how did it not get the kind of media attention that "Crash" got?Maybe because it was made by a debut "Generation X" director, Greg Marcks. Like "Donnie Darko" director Richard Kelly before him, Marcks got shafted on the publicity machine. I saw "Crash" in theaters and really liked it. But for all its clever coincidences, I found the story quite unbelievably contrived (as the film characters are connected in surprising ways, which takes place in the huge megatropolis of Los Angeles). When I read the description for "11:14", it sounded a lot like "Crash" but came out a year or two earlier. After watching it, let me tell you...I have never had such a mind-blowing experience watching a film before. This film had me riveted as I watched how all the story segments fall into place. By the end of the movie, I was like "whoa!" Brilliant, man. Absolutely brilliant!Like the movie "Crash", this one involves a couple car accidents and the ways the people involved are all connected to one another. To reveal any more is to ruin the film experience. All I can say is that the performances were really good. I've been a fan of Henry Thomas since "E.T.", since he is the same age as me and I related to his Elliot character back then. He's a good actor who deserves to be in more films. Patrick Swayze in this reminds me of the small but pivotal role he played in "Donnie Darko", which leads me to wonder why he's playing in such minor roles, being directed by Generation X director. Barbara Hershey, another actress I like from the 1980s, seems to reprise her role in the film "Lantana", but this role is simply too small, but she manages it well. However, I think this film showcases the talents of Sean Hatosy, who is becoming one of my favorite actors by how well he makes his facial expressions. From "Soldier Girl" to "Faith of My Fathers" to "11:14", I really hope his career launches into more leading man status or at least a buddy film. He is definitely the actor to watch.When the final scene occurs and all the pieces fall together, I was so amazed by its brilliance that I had to watch it again, and then again with the director's commentary track. This is a film that I would've seen in theaters had it been better publicized and distributed. As far as first films go, you can't get better than this. Like director Richard Kelly, I believe Greg Marcks is another one to watch. If you enjoyed "Crash" and "Memento", you'll probably love this film as well. And memo to Hollywood...don't be afraid to take risks on unconventional storylines. This movie far exceeds the formulaic action/romantic-comedy/suspense films you dish out to audiences year after year. This film leaves a lasting impression and really blows your mind away with its implication. Its what every viewer wants to experience when they watch a movie.
summary: If you thought "Crash" was a mind-blowing movie...you haven't seen this!

reviewText: Picture 'Pulp Fiction' only with a dismembered member and a man getting his face caved in during sex only to have it eaten by a dog, and you might get a sense of the madness that goes down at 11:14. The film is very cleverly written and directed by Greg Marcks. Focusing on a handful of interweaving stories occurring at 11:14, weird things happen and people collide in surprising ways. At the center of it all is a manipulative girl (a sexy Rachael Leigh Cook) who has three men wrapped around her finger. Her religious dad (a creepy and funny Patrick Swayze) goes overboard protecting and following his little girl around. A drunk driver (Henry Thomas) has an accident when something thrown from a bridge smashes through his windshield. Figuring it's a deer, he's horrified to discover it's a mutilated body. A concerned driver (Barbara Hershey) pulls up next to him and calls the cops before taking off. When the officer (Clark Gregg) arrives to administer a sobriety test he already has two people (Hilary Swank and Shawn Hatosy) in his backseat. The driver makes a break for it and so do the other two. On the other side of town, a trio of rowdy teens (Colin Hanks, Ben Foster and Stark Sands) drive around in a van destroying property. What happens to one of them is horrifying and hilarious, involving a retrieval mission like you've never seen. In another part of town, two convenience store employees come up with a plan to rob the store and then rig it to look like an armed robbery. They aren't the criminal masterminds they think and one winds up shooting the other by accident. Every performance rocks, with standouts being Hilary Swank, looking sexy in braces, and Colin Hanks who's just as likable as his dad. The film's an extremely fun ride that seems confusing at times but makes total sense at the end.

reviewText: 11:14 (Greg Marcks, 2003)I can think 11:14 for disabusing me of one of my most long-held hypotheses: that if you take an event, no matter how improbable, and illuminate all the seemingly logical chains of events leading up to that one vastly improbable event, you can make it seem like the most natural thing in the world. This is what 11:14 attempts to do, and it fails. However, it fails in quite a spectacular, and watchable, manner.11:14 opens with a drunk driver, Jack (All the Pretty Horses' Henry Thomas), on his cell phone, trying to placate someone. There is a collision. Jack gets out and finds a dead man in front of his car. Things get worse from there. But, we quickly find out, the events that play out over the next few minutes are the end of the timeline here; the accident occurs at 11:14, and the bulk of the movie deals with five stories that lead up to that time, setting up everything that went into this accident happening exactly the way it did. The idea, presumably, is to make the rather ludicrous event (you realize just how ludicrous it is about halfway through) seem plausible, and on this level, it not only fails, but it fails in quite amazing fashion. Rather than becoming plausible, things keep getting more and more outrageous. If you're capable of suspending your disbelief through the second half of the movie, you're a better man than I, Charlie Brown. But the outrageousness of the whole situation is one of the things that makes the movie so much fun. Marcks takes a bunch of unbelievable characters, gets an incredible cast to portray them, and then follows this idea down the weirdest roads he could think of.All of which is great, except that it fizzles out about an hour in. We get the last of the pieces falling into place, and we're left with about twenty or thirty minutes of movie to watch. On the cutting board, this would have been a minor thing; rearrange a few scenes and poof, problem solved. (Continuity is not one of the movie's strong points, and I'm pretty sure that was by design.) However, we're stuck with the order we've got, and we have a climax that comes roughly fifteen minutes too early, leaving us with a denouement we see coming from a mile off, without any ambiguousness to keep us wondering.A good effort for a debut feature. Marcks will need to step up his game for movie number two, but he won't have to step it up too much. ***
summary: Pretty good for a first movie.

reviewText: "11:14," a 2003 independent film by writer/director Greg Marcks, is a thriller that settles into a complicated spellbinder that grips the viewer and does not let go.  Much like the beginning of "Identity," to which this film obviously owes at least a bit of directorial inspiration, a series of apparently random events are all inexorably tied together, binding the unwitting characters in an inescapable chain of cause and effect...and at 11:14 on this fateful night, these forces all come together.Cleverly unfolded, the story introduces us to an eventual ensemble of about a dozen characters, only some of whom are actually central to the proceedings; but the director does not let on until the end who these crucial characters are, or how they are connected.  The compelling, if initially confusing way the story is told only adds to the drama, as events are lived and relived from different perspectives as things go on.  Indeed, even as connections begin to become clear, it is not until moments before the end credits begin to roll that the viewer realizes that the story has come full circle and that, in fact, there HAS been a driving force behind all that has transpired.If there are any quibbles about this film the central one would be that Mr. Marcks put together an impressive cast of veterans such as Hillary Swank, Barbara Hershey and Patrick Swayze, but did not use them at all to their fullest.  Rather, and this could reflect the audience he hoped to attract, the camera spends an inordinate amount of time focused on essentially unknown young newcomers like Shawn Hatosy and Stark Sands, often in unsympathetic and patently dumb situations.  At times sinking to the level of a summer release gross-out flick or Dead Teenager movie, and thereby threatening to lose anyone over the age of 25, the film is ultimately rescued by the overarching storyline and Marcks' generally taut direction.  The ending, at first blush, leaves many questions unanswered, and also leaves the viewer with a vague sense of injustice.  But Marcks has been clever to touch just about every "victim" with just enough culpability so that only one player can honestly and justifiably cry Foul.This is not really a "who dunnit," because, in one way or another, they almost all done it.  But it is a satisfying, engaging effort that deserves to be seen.

reviewText: This movie has a lot in common with the Academy Award nominated movie "Crash," but it doesn't strive to make heavy race relations, social commentary. It's just a tightly-woven essay on the randomness of things. (What could be more random than the hour of 11:14?)If you did want to impute a larger significance to the movie, you could say it's an illustration of chaos theory's "butterfly effect." When a butterfly in Brazil flaps its wings, a chain reaction is started, and a typhoon blows out the lives of thousands of people in Indonesia. And so it is here. When three teen buddies decide to go joy-riding, their most casual shenanigans intertwine with the shenanigans of other people - and result in a typhoon in everyone's lives.All the acting is good and engaging. Patrick Swayze looks the part of the conscientious, weighted-with-worry father as he tries to keep tabs on his rebellious daughter. Hillary Swank, with braces on her teeth, looks the part of the young convenience store clerk who gets caught in the consequences of a casual scheme to lift some money from the store till.This film held my interest, following the twists and turns of fate as it had its way with all the characters.

reviewText: A man driving while talking on his phone hits something in the road.  A father watches his daughter leave the house.  A store clerk plans a staged robbery so he can take the money in the register.  Some young men driving around in his parent's van hit a girl in the road, resulting in a Bobbitt-like injury to one of the young men.The young men are vandals, the daughter hatching a devious scheme, the driver was drunk, the store clerks are stupid, and the plot twists and thickens.  All is not quiet in Middleton tonight, and at 11:14PM tragedy occurs when all these lives entwine.Patrick Swayze and Barbara Hershey give decent performances in '11:14', but were not given much to work with as far as script or emotion.  The film is quite interesting in many places, but once finished left a flat taste in my mouth.  There just was too little coming from too many subplots.  Blood, but not enough.  Intrigue, but too guessable.  Emotion, but a little flat.  Deception, but too common.  Graveyard hanky-panky, but not depraved enough.  And while the ending brought everything together, nothing in particular stood out as being desperately despicable.This is a good movie to rent and watch, but I don't recommend purchasing it.  Enjoy!
summary: All paths lead towards the same destination

reviewText: This was an interesting, entertaining film as far as gimmicks go, but in the end it left me unsatisfied.Like a lot of movies today, the premise revolves around a series of seemingly random stories that all intersect.  In this one, the lives of several people in a small town all come together at exactly 11:14.  Throughout the 90 minute movie you see the story of half a dozen characters (Henry Thomas, a group of boys, Patrick Swayze, Hillary Swank, Shawn Hatosy, Rachel Leigh Cook).  As the movie progresses, you begin to see how all the stories come together, but it's not until the last minute of the film that you can see the entire picture.It's an interesting way to make a movie, and it certainly keeps you guessing until the end, the problem is that a lot of films today are using this gimmick of intersecting story lines, and this is far from the best.  The acting from several of the characters is poor, and in the end the stories leave you wanting more of a resolution--you know what happens to everyone at 11:14, but what happens after?

reviewText: Director:  Greg MarcksCast:  Rachael Leigh Cook, Barbara Hershey, Patrick Swayze, Hilary Swank, Ben Foster, Clark Gregg, Colin Hanks, Shawn Hatosy, Stark Sands, Henry Thomas.Rated R for violence, language, and a sex scene.Running Time:  85 minutes.Virtually unnoticed after its original completion in 2003, "11:14" makes an adequate attempt at the "Memento" genre with its twists and turns that closely resemble the superb drama "Crash" (which was released nearly a year and a half later).  Director Greg Marcks, making his directorial debut, does a fine job setting the arena for a gripping and moderately witty foundation, but his rookie film seems rushed and the final payoff leaves much to be desired.The film takes place in the small town of Middletown, which represents every small little slab of Americana this fine country has to offer.  "11:14" begins with the bourbon-buzzed Henry Thomas (child star of "E.T.") accidentally crashing into a man while driving on the highway, killing him on impact.  Thomas is interrogated by a local police officer, who discovers what the drunk has done and attempts to arrest him.  As Thomas escapes, this is when Marcks launches the audience into a frenzy of intertwined moments in time:  A mother (played by Barbara Hershey) learns that her daughter is fatally killed in a hit-and-run accident, a father (Patrick Swayze) finds a dead man in the cemetery right outside of his home, a poor buck named Duffy (Shawn Hatosy, who gives the finest performance of the ensemble cast) must hold up his own convenience store to steal money for his girlfriend's abortion, three roguish high-schoolers drunkenly parade around in a fan, setting off fires and peeing out of the windows, a store clerk (a brace-faced Hilary Swank) must choose between helping her friend or her sister's health, and a sluttish school-girl (Rachel Leigh Cook) devises a plan to make some quick cash."11:14" is a clever stab at asking the questions "do coincidences exist?" and "what happens when we aren't responsible for our own actions?", piecing all of these at-first trivial events into a puzzle of murder, deceit, and mischief that is only at times entertaining.  Cook and Swayze are wastes in their small roles, while Swank is once again at the top of her game as the geeky convenience store clerk who is caught between a rock and a hard place.  Promoted as a dark comedy, the film possesses some tongue-in-cheek smirks at life, but doesn't get everything out of its script (also written by Marcks) and its supposed superb cast that it should have.  Fans of the "Crash" and "21 Grams" style will enjoy, but those looking for an in-depth drama that focuses on characterization, plot-development, and superb acting may want to look at films such as "Magnolia".  Good, but certainly not one of the best of its kind.

reviewText: Mixture of crime and comedy told with multiple viewpoints is no longer a new thing after "Pulp Fiction," but the impression of "11:14" is closer to Doug Liman's "go" (1999), of which tagline goes "Life begins at 3 am." Greg Marcks' film starts earlier, but the tone is slightly darker.The film, which starts with one strange car accident involving a dead body falling from up above, skillfully puts together a range of different perspectives. More strange and bizarre accidents are to happen later in the film and those characters played by Hilary Swank (also co-executive producer), Henry Thomas, Blake Heron, Barbara Hershey, Clark Gregg, Shawn Hatosy, Stark Sands, Colin Hanks, Ben Foster, Patrick Swayze and Rachael Leigh Cook, make serious (and hilarious) mistakes.Hilary Swank's convenience store clerk "Buzzy" and gunshots part is most interesting and so is the freak accident that happens to one drunken teenage boy in the van. Both episodes end up with terrible and painful results which will make the viewers laugh a lot.But for me as the film went on, it became less and less interesting. It's like jigsaw puzzle and as the pieces are put in the right places, there are no more surprises coming from the finished parts. In Tarantino, round characters like Mia, Vincent and Jules never bored us with superb acting from Uma Thurman, John Travolta and Samuel L. Jackson all speaking the dialogues you never forget. Here some characters are disappointingly flat such as Rachael Leigh Cook's flirting daughter and Patrick Swayze's concerned father. Tarantino would have milked their scenes for more surprising jokes (like the dead body in the backseat and Harvey Keitel's cleaner episode). In "11:14" we can predict what is coming after seeing Rachael Leigh Cook's character and her boyfriend enter the graveyard."11:14" is an entertaining dark comedy and the director has a flair for making unique comic scenes, though it is also true that I felt I had seen them before while watching.
summary: Entertaining Dark Comedy, Still Hardly Groundbreaking
